A wide range of Jesus peoples practiced gender bending—that is, gender roles were fluid and flexible. One of their primary identities was that they were neither male nor female, but all were “one” through different lived, experienced realities of gender pluralism. Women, and a significant number of men, rejected both male dominance and female passivity. A wide swath of Jesus groups rejected marriage and traditional families, with the envoy Paul often leading the way. Although some Anointed groups and individuals supported male dominance and demanded female obedience to men, many men shifted toward acting more vulnerable and less domineering. Women cut their hair and dressed like men. These gendered activities and actions brokered new possibilities for identity among various Jesus peoples, well beyond the regular masculine/feminine dichotomies of the first two centuries.
They Lived in Chosen Families
With traditional families increasingly broken and dispersed, a variety of Jesus groups started living in experimental family groups. These new family groups were voluntary; that is, they lived together increasingly outside of blood or married relationships. Whereas previously the primary relations for living arrangements were extended families of multiple generations with cousins, aunts, and uncles in the mix, Jesus people associated daily with each other according to mutual support and affection. More and more “supper clubs” became crucial and core associations of daily life. Economic sharing provided ways that members of these groups bonded. In some cases, larger housing arrangements came into play for the groups through a donor exhibiting compassion. Although most of these new kinds of families were small, occasionally a wealthy person provided larger space for bigger groups.

I’d say most common plan in the US is:
2mg SL(sublingual) for months 0-3
4mg SL for months 3-6
6mg SL for months 6-9 (if labs or symptoms support increase)
6-8mg SL months 9-12 (do not go up to 8mg labs or symptoms support increase or if you’re terrible at dissolving your SL)

Most common AA path is:
50mg spiro 2x daily
Sometimes go up to 100mg spiro 2x daily around 3mo
Higher spiro only if labs support.

In the US you have a lot of freedom as basically all forms of e can be prescribed here. However, it’s harder to get alternative AAs. Read OP graphic and decide on a preferred method in case your endo gives you the choice.

>>29074056
Probably not tbhon. Explanation:

Your testosterone levels rise after exercise, especially intense, heavy strength training. This increase in level may last just 15 minutes or up to an hour. PMABs often experience a greater and longer rise in testosterone when they strength train in the evening, as opposed to the morning. New exercisers get a bigger boost, too, but over time their hormone levels adapt.

Research has yet to show the absolute effects of this increase, but it’s likely not enough to make a change in the way you feel or anything. If you have borderline levels, a regular exercise habit may be enough to bump you up slightly from where you’d ideally want to be but generally bodies adapt and AAs work well.

>Sounds good, is it work getting a trainer? Never been to the gym before so I'm clueless on how to actually do any of these exercises properly
Mmm, I really want to learn about this stuff a bit more on your own, but as an absolute beginner getting a trainer isn't a bad idea, unless they're a complete retard they should be able to help you with the basics, like, the correct squatting technique and whatnot. But you absolutely want to look into it on your own as well. Trainers like to bs their clients, and in many gyms the only requirement to become a trainer is literally having a pulse.
Also, I should clarify the "upper body" thing because I said that you shouldn't train it, but then said that you needed to train your back. What I meant was not training your chest, shoulders, and arms directly. Training your back is fine, there's just caveats.
For legs and ass you want to prioritise free weights, but for back training you should consider machines because they allow for better isolation (working on specific muscle groups).
Also, don't overcomplicate your routine, you're a beginner. There's no point in that, you need to get familiar with your body, you need to learn how to feel your muscles. Warm up, then do some squats, romanian deadlifts, and lunges, and that will be enough for your legs and ass. Add some rope/cable face pulls for your upper back and hyperextensions (can be weighted, but that's for more advanced lifters) for your spinal erectors, ass, and hamstrings. I actually do hyperextensions as a warm up before Romanian dead lifts.
Super simple, super chill, no bs.

>but how are you supposed to go 5x a week if you're avoiding chest, shoulders and arms? you cant work on your lower body every day, that can slow down your progress and/or over-train you.
Why would you go to the gym 5 times a week when 3 is enough for the vast majority of people? If I really had to "work out" 5 days a week, I'd just add 2 cardio (LISS) or yoga days to the mix. Even pre-transition when I was training really hard and also casually competed in powerlifting I always trained every other day because having rest days is important. It's not even about your muscles, it's about mental fatigue, your CNS (central nervous system) needs to rest as well.
Also, you REALLY CAN'T get "overtrained" as a casual gym goer. The most susceptible to actual overtraining are crossfit athletes, especially high level ones, and even among them it's really rare. And they hit the same muscle groups at very high volumes every single workout.
Here's a good video from a respectable guy with a PhD in Sport Physiology: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DSqMbbkDDA
TL;DR, it's an ancient myth that needs to die, relax.
Overall, no shade, but you might not be training as hard as you think you do.

Lunges for quads (and a bit for glutes, they assist as stabilisers).
Romanian deadlifts or RDLs for the hamstrings, glutes, and lower back (very beginner friendly, but are good even for advanced lifters).
Hip thrusts for glutes (they're the best, but I wouldn't recommend weighted hip thrusts for absolute beginners, and RDLs are significantly better than unweighted hip thrusts).

Wait a second, are you workouts just short? Like, <30 minutes a day or something? Given that you're a beginner (at least from what I understand) you generally shouldn't have more than 2 exercises per muscle group. That's like under 10-15 minutes total including the warmup.
If you're a beginner there's no need to do a lot of isolation and accessory/additional exercises, you're better off focusing on basic compound movements like squats, bench, and deads because they hit a lot of muscles at once and as a beginner literally everything in your body is weak and untrained :v At best you want to add one accessory to each of those to target some lacking areas. For instance, when you squat and realise that your quads are particularly weak, especially if you can't even maintain your form, you should add an additional more isolated exercise for quads, like, leg extensions or lunges to strengthen them. And then you do both of them, over time your quads will catch up, and then you'll realise that something else started lagging behind, let's say, your lower back can't handle the weight anymore, so you switch those leg extensions out for hyperextensions or good mornings (might be too complex for a beginner), you don't just add more accessories on top of accessories.
I also fell into this trap of doing too many different exercises instead of focusing on the fundamentals when I was just starting out ages ago... The same goes for supplements, ugh, embarrassing memories >_>
I'm not trying to be patronising, I'm sorry, I'm just trying to explain how to optimise the time you spend in the gym.

Encouraging you to examine your own thoughts and feelings is basically all they do. They will hardly ever prompt a new thought for you themselves, or prompt a new thought in yourself either.
Basically it's like having a dialog with a mirror. Some people just dont self-examine so a dialog or venting to another is helpful, but for most it isn't.
They wont give you any leg work, give you goals, give you any interesting angles to think about, UNLESS you have literally never self reflected, and only a good one is going push you in any sort of direction, and still only based on the feelings you understand enough to articulate.

LSD is helpful because it literally inhibits all the programming you've accumulated and habits of thought you currently have, at the same time as putting you in a headspace where you are highly reprogrammable. You can literally change your stances and feelings you've held since you were a child, with just a thought.
Lose a phobia in a 12 hour period you've held all your life. Change the way you see this or that effortlessly in real time.
And also you just feel like a new person after you take it, which is really helpful when your trying to change yourself for the better. A good trip, at the worst, you'll at least feel fucking refreshed when it's over. It's amazing, and before it was made illegal basically was the for-front for treating all sorts of mental illnesses. It still is pretty much the best treatment.

Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!
